    "name": "COU1: Cardiopulmonary bypass use (Class II)",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to evaluate the sensitivity of pump-induced hemolysis to variations in component dimensions for a centrifugal blood pump used during cardiopulmonary bypass surgery. Model influence is MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect tolerance decision could impact clinical hemolysis levels). Model Risk Level 2.",
    "deviceClass": "Class II",
    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to identify worst-case operating conditions for hemolysis across 5 flow-speed combinations for a Class II CPB device. Results compared against predicate device hemolysis using relative hemolysis index (RH < 1 acceptance criterion).",
    "hasOperatingEnvelope": {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou1-cpb/operating-envelope",
      "type": "OperatingEnvelope",
      "name": "CPB hemolysis CFD operating envelope — bounded flow, speed, and hematocrit",
      "description": "The model is valid within the following explicitly bounded operating conditions: volumetric flow rate 1.0–7.0 L/min (five nominal set-points: 1, 2, 3, 5, 7 L/min); impeller rotational speed 1500–3500 RPM (four nominal speeds: 1500, 2000, 2500, 3500 RPM); inlet hematocrit 35–45% (nominal 40%); blood temperature 35–38 °C; outlet pressure head 50–350 mmHg. Impeller tip clearance tolerance ±0.05 mm around nominal 0.30 mm. Volute gap tolerance ±0.08 mm around nominal 0.50 mm. Predictions outside these bounds are not supported by the validation evidence and require a separate credibility assessment."
    },
    "hasApplicabilityConstraint": {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou1-cpb/applicability-constraint",
      "type": "ApplicabilityConstraint",
      "name": "CPB hemolysis CFD applicability constraint — Class II adult CPB circuits only",
      "description": "This credibility assessment applies exclusively to: (1) the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump geometry (GCBP v2 CAD baseline) and geometric variants within the stated tolerance band; (2) adult patients (body surface area 1.5–2.2 m²) on normothermic or mild hypothermic CPB; (3) Newtonian blood rheology approximation valid for shear rates above 100 s⁻¹; (4) steady-state or quasi-steady-state operating conditions (no transient start-up or emergency stop scenarios). Pediatric circuits, pulsatile-assist modes, and non-Newtonian dominated low-shear regimes are explicitly out of scope."
    }
  },
